"I rather like Rebel IPA a lot, but it does little to stand out among the ranks of bolder and more complex beers of its style. But pairing well with great company, pizza, cheeseburgers and savory appetizers gives this ale a welcome home."
"West Coast IPA (or California Hop Bomb if you will) happens to be one of my most favorite style of beer in the world, so I was immediately intrigued when I saw this Samuel Adams beer in the shop today. They certainly nailed the look, as this was clear as they come, golden amber in color, and exhibited a steady stream of bubbles feeding a two finger thick head. The smell was a little disappointing, as I was expecting a pine and grapefruit explosion. Instead I got a subdued citrus and a hint of spruce. The taste was even less authentic than the smell, as there was none of the expected bracing hop bitterness. Instead it tasted like a bland extract of hops, with a sweetness like toffee, and a peppery finish. This was certainly nowhere like a West Coast style beer. The mouthfeel was decent, with a sticky coating on the tongue. This just came into the store today, and has a best by date of June 2014, so why does it taste so bland? If you really want a West Coast style IPA brewed on the East Coast, get a Jai Alai. That is some seriously hoppy stuff."
